{
  "text": "Recently, a number of studies reported that molecular phenotypes correlated with the presence of RNA foci [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Two of these studies corrected the observed phenotype by targeted degradation of the foci using antisense oligonucleotides [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . One study suggested that foci burden in the frontal cortex positively correlated with disease severity in eight patients with C9orf72 frontotemporal degeneration [CITATION_8] . Two of these reports identified co-localization of RNA foci with various proteins [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] and suggested that pathogenic sequestration might be occurring. A similar process has been observed in myotonic dystrophy type 1, another neuromuscular disease caused by an intronic expansion [CITATION_11] . Previously two groups generated candidate binding partners of the GGGGCC repeat expansion, but did not include co-localization studies with RNA foci [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] . Further work to characterize protein binding partners of the RNA foci is required, particularly because many of the studies thus far are in disagreement as to the most important interactions.",
  "correct_citation": {
